GEOB 308 FRASER LOWLAND FIELD TRIP

Figure 1. Generalized surficial geology of the Fraser Lowland. Adapted, in part, from Armstrong, (1980a, b) and Armstrong and Hicock (1980a, b).

Introduction

Interpreting landforms and surficial materials in the field is an integral part of the geomorphologists art. To help you further understand the Quaternary history of the region, and to apply some of the theory we have explored in lecture and in the labs, this virtual field trip will introduce you to Quaternary sedimentary deposits and landforms across the Fraser Lowland.

Throughout the Quaternary, British Columbia has been repeatedly covered by extensive lobes of ice that have periodically coalesced to form a large continental ice sheet, the Cordilleran Ice Sheet. As a result, the surficial materials and landforms throughout much of the province reflect erosion and deposition from repeated Pleistocene glaciation, and generally bear no relationship to the underlying lithology (Clague and Luternauer, 1983). The Fraser Lowland experienced both repeated glaciations and deglaciations during the late Quaternary period, along with associated sea level transgressions and regressions. The fact that both a continental ice sheet and local sea level fluctuated in and out of this area for thousands of years, depositing a massive amount of sediment, has created a complex present-day landscape with various different Quaternary deposit types, providing the ideal substrate for a wide variety of land uses. Knowledge of glacial and de-glacial processes is therefore central to understanding the nature and distribution of surficial materials, which in turn dictate land use practices. This field investigation of the various surficial deposits and landforms around the Vancouver region will enable us to develop a reconstruction of the glacial and deglacial history of the region, and to explore how glacial processes and deposits affect current land uses

The surficial deposits of the Fraser lowland consist primarily of sediments deposited during the advance and retreat of the Puget Lobe of the Cordilleran Ice Sheet, approximately 20,000-11,000 years ago. Situated near the ice sheet-ocean margin, the Fraser lowland therefore experienced a complex glacial history with numerous transgressions and regressions of sea level due to isostatic changes resulting from repeated glaciations and deglaciations, resulting in a striking diversity of surficial deposits including glaciomarine, glaciofluvial, fluvial, ice stagnation, glacio-lacustrine, and till deposits. Based on the complex drift packages found throughout the Fraser lowland, Ryder and Clague (1989) identified three separate stades of glacial advance during the Fraser glaciation: 1) an early advance represented by the Coquitlam drift, 2) a more extensive advance which produced the Vashon drift 3) a brief glacial re-advance termed the Sumas drift (figure 1). The various types of Quaternary deposits and their spatial distribution controls land use in the Fraser valley, with different facies types providing an ideal substrate for a variety of land uses, such as berry farms and vineyards, aggregate extraction sites, livestock farms and urban infrastructure.
